## Timestep and Delta-Time Handling

### `Timestep`

**File:** `Code/PigeonLib/Pigeon/Core/Timestep.h`

Wraps a `uint64_t` representing milliseconds since the engine epoch.

```cpp
class Timestep
{
public:
    explicit Timestep(uint64_t time = 0) noexcept;
    explicit Timestep(std::chrono::milliseconds duration) noexcept;

    operator uint64_t() const noexcept;          // implicit cast to raw ms value

    float    AsMinutes()      const noexcept;    // ms / 1000 / 60
    float    AsSeconds()      const noexcept;    // ms / 1000
    uint64_t AsMilliseconds() const noexcept;    // raw ms
};
```

The implicit `operator uint64_t()` means a `Timestep` can be stored and passed as `uint64_t` without an explicit cast.

### `Clock`

**File:** `Code/PigeonLib/Pigeon/Core/Clock.h`

Thin wrapper around `std::chrono::steady_clock`.

```cpp
class Clock
{
public:
    Clock();                                // records construction time as starting_point
    const Timestep Elapsed() const noexcept; // ms since construction / last Restart
    const Timestep Restart() noexcept;       // returns elapsed ms, resets starting_point
};
```

**How delta-time reaches systems:** `Application::UpdateApp()` calls `m_ClockFrameTime.Restart()` which yields the duration since the last `Restart()` (i.e., since the previous frame). This `Timestep` is passed to `Application::Update(ts)`, stored in `m_Data.m_LastFrameTime`, and forwarded unchanged to `World::Update(ts)`, which forwards it to every registered `System::Update(ts)`.

